# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-rising
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The **2021 United Nations Climate Change Conference**, more commonly referred to as **COP26**, was the 26th United Nations Climate Change conference, held at the SEC Centre in Glasgow, Scotland, United Kingdom, from 31 October to 13 November 2021.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The president of the conference was UK cabinet minister Alok Sharma.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The result of COP26 was the Glasgow Climate Pact, negotiated through consensus of the representatives of the 197 attending parties.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Owing to late interventions from India and China that weakened a move to end coal power and fossil fuel subsidies, the conference ended with the adoption of a less stringent resolution than some anticipated.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Nevertheless, the pact was the first climate deal to explicitly commit to reducing the use of coal.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] It included wording that encouraged more urgent greenhouse gas emissions cuts and promised more climate finance for developing countries to adapt to climate impacts.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In the midst of the conference, on 6 November 2021, a march against inadequate action at the conference, as well as for other climate change-related issues, became the largest protest in Glasgow since anti-Iraq War marches in 2003.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Additional rallies took place in 100 other countries.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The United Kingdom holds the presidency of COP26 until the start of COP27.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Initially, the Minister of State for Energy and Clean Growth, Claire Perry, was appointed as president of the conference, but she was removed on 31 January 2020, several months after she had stepped down as an MP.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Former Prime Minister David Cameron and former Foreign Secretary William Hague declined to take the role.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 13 February 2020, Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy Secretary Alok Sharma was appointed.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 8 January 2021, Sharma was succeeded by Kwasi Kwarteng as Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy Secretary and moved to the Cabinet Office, in order to focus on the presidency full-time.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Nigel Topping, the former CEO of climate change action organization We Mean Business, was appointed the UK Government's High Level Climate Action Champion for COP26.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Italy partnered with the UK in leading COP26.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] For the most part, their role was in preparatory work such as the hosting of a pre-COP session and an event for young people called Youth4Climate 2020: Driving Ambition.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] These events took place between 28 September and 2 October 2020 in Milan.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Because of the COVID-19 pandemic, in April 2020 the conference was postponed to 31 October – 12 November 2021.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Both host countries, Italy and the UK, were heavily affected by the pandemic, and the venue of the conference, the SEC Centre in Glasgow, was converted in May 2020 into a temporary hospital for COVID-19 patients in Scotland.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Earlier in 2021, the UK and Italy hosted summits of the G7 and G20, respectively.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Independent observers noted that though not directly related, the postponement gave the international community time to respond to the outcome of the United States presidential election, held in November 2020.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] President Donald Trump had withdrawn the United States from the Paris Agreement, although this could not take effect until the day after the election; while his Democratic challengers pledged to immediately rejoin and increase ambition to reduce greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Joe Biden did so upon being elected as president.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] At the conference, Biden apologized for Trump's withdrawal from the agreement.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Previous summits have been sponsored by fossil fuel companies.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] To reduce this influence, the UK government decided that sponsors "have to have real commitments in place to help them reach net zero in the near future".
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The first principal partners included three British energy companies and a banking and insurance company.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Before the summit councils in and around Glasgow pledged to plant 18 million trees during the following decade: the Clyde Climate Forest (CCF) is projected to increase tree coverage in the urban areas of the Greater Glasgow region to 20%.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In September 2021, the conference was urged by Climate Action Network to ensure attendees would be able to attend in spite of travel restrictions related to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In the months before the conference, the British government had restrictions on travel from certain countries in place, and COVID passports were required in certain venues.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Critics suggested unequal deployment of COVID-19 vaccines worldwide could exclude the participation of representatives of poorer countries most affected by climate change.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The UK subsequently relaxed travel rules for delegations.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Only four Pacific Islands nations sent delegations due to COVID-19 travel restrictions, with most island nations compelled to send smaller teams than they otherwise would have.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Organizers have in place numerous COVID-19 rules for attendees, dependent on vaccination status.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 4 June 2021, a nighttime light projection onto the Tolbooth Steeple was installed, under the Climate Clock initiative.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The projected Deadline and Lifeline statistics count the time window before 1.5 °C warming would become inevitable, and the percentage of global energy delivered through renewables, respectively.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The Scottish Events Campus (SEC), known as the Blue Zone, temporarily became United Nations territory: the other main venue is the Green Zone at Glasgow Science Centre.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The summit was described as receiving "the cleanest electricity in the UK", as 70% was supplied from low-carbon nuclear power from plants in Torness and Hunterston B, while the rest mostly came from wind power.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The provision of medical services for the event was provided by BASICS Scotland, Amvale Medical and the Scottish Ambulance Service.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The medical centre was visited by both Scottish National Clinical Director Jason Leitch and Scottish Health Secretary Humza Yousaf during the conference.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Twenty-five thousand delegates from nearly 200 countries were expected to attend, and around 120 heads of state came.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Australian prime minister Scott Morrison spoke.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Czech prime minister Andrej Babiš denounced the proposed European Union Fit for 55 laws, part of the European Green Deal, saying that the bloc "can achieve nothing without the participation of the largest polluters such as China or the USA".
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Prince Charles addressed the opening ceremony in person.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Queen Elizabeth, having been advised to rest by doctors, addressed the conference by video message.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Bill Gates called for a "green industrial revolution" to beat the climate crisis.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The fossil fuel industry was the largest delegation at the conference, with 503 people accredited.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In October 2021, China's leader Xi Jinping announced he would not be attending the conference in person and instead delivered a written address as the organizers did not provide an opportunity for a video address.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] With greenhouse gas emissions by China being the world's largest, Reuters said this made it less likely the conference would result in a significant climate deal.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] However, a Chinese delegation led by climate change envoy Xie Zhenhua did attend.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The 2021 global energy crisis intensified pressures on China ahead of the summit.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The prime ministers or heads of state of South Africa, Russia, Saudi Arabia, Iran, Mexico, Brazil, Turkey, Malaysia and Vatican City also did not attend the meeting.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Russian president Vladimir Putin said his non-attendance was due to concerns relating to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Iranian president Ebrahim Raisi did not attend; a formal request had been made by Struan Stevenson and Iranian exiles of the National Council of Resistance of Iran to the Scotland police, to arrest Raisi for crimes against humanity if he attended based on the legal concept of universal jurisdiction.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Saudi crown prince Mohammed bin Salman also did not attend the summit.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Brazilian president Jair Bolsonaro, who faced international condemnation over rising deforestation of the Amazon rainforest, also decided not to attend the summit personally.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The non-attendance of both Putin and Xi received criticism from U.S. president Joe Biden and former American president Barack Obama.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Myanmar and Afghanistan were entirely absent; both countries had their UN-recognized governments ousted militarily in 2021.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The Myanmar military junta was blocked from entry to the summit.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Six exiled Afghan climate experts had their applications rejected by the UNFCCC.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Additionally, the island nation of Kiribati did not send participants, while fellow island nations Vanuatu and Samoa registered but did not send a delegation.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Under the Paris Agreement, countries submitted pledges called nationally determined contributions, to limit their greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Under the framework of the Paris Agreement, each country is expected to submit enhanced nationally determined contributions every five years, to ratchet up the ambition to mitigate climate change.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] When the Paris Agreement was signed at COP21, the conference of 2020 was set to be the first ratcheting up.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Even though the 2020 conference was postponed to 2021 due to the COVID-19 pandemic, dozens of countries still had not updated their pledges by early October 2021.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Collective progress towards implementation of the Paris Agreement in mitigation, adaptation and finance flows and means of implementation and support will be measured by global stocktakes, the first of which is due to be completed in 2023.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 13 November 2021, the participating 197 countries agreed to a new deal, known as the Glasgow Climate Pact, aimed at staving off dangerous climate change.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The final agreement explicitly mentions coal, which is the single biggest contributor to climate change.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Previous COP agreements have not mentioned coal, oil or gas, or even fossil fuels in general, as a driver, or major cause of climate change, making the Glasgow Climate Pact the first ever climate deal to explicitly plan to reduce unabated coal power.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The wording in the agreement refers to an intention to "phase down" use of unabated coal power, rather than to phase it out.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] From this wording it implicitly follows that utilizing coal power with "abation" (net-zero emission), e.g. by neutralizing the resulting carbon dioxide via the CO2-to-stone process, need not be reduced.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] However, this carbon capture and storage is too expensive for most coal fired power stations.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Over 140 countries pledged to reach net-zero emissions.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] More than 100 countries, including Brazil, pledged to reverse deforestation by 2030.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The final text of the Glasgow Climate Pact include a call to: "accelerating efforts towards... phase-out of inefficient fossil fuel subsidies".
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] More than 40 countries pledged to move away from coal.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The United States and China reached an agreement about cooperation on measures to stop climate change, including lowering methane emissions, phasing out the use of coal, and forest conservation.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] 39 countries and institutions signed the Glasgow Statement, an international agreement to shift international public finance away from fossil fuels towards clean energy.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] If implemented properly, the Glasgow Statement will shift $28 billion per year from fossil fuels to clean energy.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] India promised to draw half of its energy requirement from renewable sources by 2030 and achieve carbon neutrality by 2070.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Governments of 24 developed countries and a group of major car manufacturers such as GM, Ford, Volvo, BYD Auto, Jaguar Land Rover, and Mercedes-Benz have committed to "work towards all sales of new cars and vans being zero emission globally by 2040, and by no later than 2035 in leading markets".
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Major car manufacturing nations like China, the US, Japan, Germany, and South Korea, as well as Toyota, Volkswagen, Nissan-Renault-Mitsubishi, Stellantis, Honda, and Hyundai had not signed up to the pledge.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] New pledges for financial help for climate change mitigation and adaptation were announced.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Climate Action Tracker on 9 November 2021, described the results as follows: the global temperature will rise by 2.7 °C by the end of the century with current policies.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The temperature will rise by 2.4 °C if only the pledges for 2030 are implemented, by 2.1 °C if the long-term targets are also achieved and by 1.8 °C if all the announced targets are fully achieved.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The Glasgow Financial Alliance for Net Zero (GFANZ) announced that financial institutions controlling $130 trillion were now signed up to 'net zero' emissions pledges by 2050.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The world leaders' summit was on 1 and 2 November, with each leader giving a national statement.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] An important goal of the conference organizers is to keep a 1.5 °C (2.7 °F) temperature rise within reach.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] According to the BBC, negotiators who may be key to the dealmaking include Xie Zhenhua, Ayman Shasly, Sheikh Hasina and Teresa Ribera.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] China said it aims to peak CO2 emissions before 2030 and to become carbon neutral by 2060.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] It was asked to set a clear earlier date as this would have a very large "positive impact" on the Paris Agreement targets.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Officials later said the 2030 target was something to "strive to" and not something to be ensured.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Signatories of the 2014 agreement, the New York Declaration on Forests, pledged to half deforestation by 2020 and end it by 2030; however, in the 2014–2020 period deforestation increased.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Indonesia's environment minister Siti Nurbaya Bakar stated that "forcing Indonesia to zero deforestation in 2030 is clearly inappropriate and unfair".
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Article 6 of the Paris Agreement, which describes rules for an international carbon market (such as for trees in the deforestation agreement) and other forms of international cooperation, is being discussed as it is the last piece of the rulebook remaining to be finalized.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Although the parties have agreed in principle to avoid double counting of emission reduction across more than one country's greenhouse gas inventory, exactly how much double counting will actually occur remains unclear.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Carrying forward pre-2020 Kyoto carbon credits will be discussed, but is highly unlikely to be agreed.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Therefore, Article 6 rules could make a big difference to future emissions.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Climate finance for adaptation and mitigation was one of the principal topics of negotiation.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Poor countries want more money for adaptation, whereas donors prefer to finance mitigation as that has a chance of making a profit.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Appointed to the role of Climate Finance Adviser was Mark Carney, former Governor of the Bank of England.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The Paris agreement included US$100 billion annually in finance by 2020 for developing countries.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] However, wealthy countries failed to live up to that promise, with members of the OECD behind in their commitments and unlikely to reach the agreed amount before 2023.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] A group of large finance companies committed to net zero portfolios and loan books by 2050.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Scotland became the first country to contribute to a loss and damage fund.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] South Africa is set to receive $8.5 billion to end its reliance on coal, details are sparse regarding capping mines, exports and local community support for the workers in the industry.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Countries including Chile, Poland, Ukraine, South Korea, Indonesia and Vietnam also agreed to phase out coal in the 2030s for major economies, and the 2040s for poorer nations.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] These nations include some of the world's most intensive users of coal.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] However, they do not include the world's largest users of the fuel, China, India, and the United States of America.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Japan is to invest $100 million in the transformation of fossil-fired plants into ones based on ammonia and hydrogen fuel.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The US and many other countries agreed to limit methane emissions.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] More than 80 countries signed up to a global methane pledge, agreeing to cut emissions by 30% by the end of the decade.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The US and European leaders say tackling the potent greenhouse gas is crucial to keeping warming limited to 1.5 °C (2.7 °F).
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Australia, China, Russia, India and Iran did not sign the deal, but it is hoped more countries will join later.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Russia demanded sanction relief on green investment projects for energy companies such as Gazprom.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Russia's climate envoy Ruslan Edelgeriyev accused Western countries of hypocrisy for urging Russia "to reduce methane leakages and yet we have Gazprom under sanctions".
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Many attendees committed to net-zero carbon emissions, with India and Japan making specific commitments at the conference.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] India, the third-largest emitter of carbon dioxide by jurisdiction, set the latest target date planning to be net-zero by 2070.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Japan is to offer up to $10 billion in additional funding to support decarbonization in Asia.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Earlier in October, China—the largest emitter of carbon dioxide by jurisdiction—had committed to net-zero carbon emissions by 2060, and it was believed by the British government that India would issue a similar commitment.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] However, this was the first time that a date for carbon neutrality had been given as part of India's climate policy.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Green hydrogen has emerged as one of the major areas where companies can collaborate to help decarbonize hard to abate industries.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Big city mayors concerned about climate—the C40 Cities Climate Leadership Group—such as Istanbul Mayor Ekrem İmamoğlu, called for more urban climate adaptation, especially in low-income countries.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] 45 countries, including the UK, U.S., Japan, Germany, India, Indonesia, Morocco, Vietnam, Philippines, Gabon, Ethiopia, Ghana and Uruguay, pledged to give more than $4 billion for transition to sustainable agriculture.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] A draft text published on 10 November asked governments to accelerate phase-outs and desubsidization of fossil fuels, the largest source of (anthropogenic) global greenhouse gas emissions, but was opposed by several countries with large fossil fuels based economic sectors.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Business leaders and politicians including Jeff Bezos, Prince Charles, Boris Johnson, Joe Biden and Angela Merkel who travelled to Glasgow in private airplanes were accused of hypocrisy by commentators and campaigners.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Event planners, however, insisted that the conference would be carbon-neutral.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Around 400 private jets arrived at Glasgow for the talks.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In October 2021, the BBC reported that a huge leak of documents revealed that Saudi Arabia, Japan and Australia were among countries asking the UN to play down the need to move rapidly away from fossil fuels.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] It also showed that some wealthy nations (including Switzerland and Australia) were questioning paying more to poorer states to move to greener technologies.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The BBC reported that the lobbying raised questions for the COP26 climate summit.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The Australian government has been criticized for hosting a fossil fuel company at the summit, not enhancing its ambitions closer to its capacities, not pledging to reduce methane emissions and not pledging to phase out coal.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In an interview shortly before the conference, Greta Thunberg, asked how optimistic she was that the conference could achieve anything, responded "Nothing has changed from previous years really.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The leaders will say 'we'll do this and we'll do this, and we will put our forces together and achieve this', and then they will do nothing.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Maybe some symbolic things and creative accounting and things that don't really have a big impact.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] By 1 November, at the outset of the conference, the climate change activist Greta Thunberg criticized the summit at a protest in Glasgow with members from the organization Fridays for Future, saying "This COP26 is so far just like the previous COPs and that has led us nowhere.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 5 November, a Fridays for Future protest at which Thunberg spoke gathered thousands of people, largely schoolchildren.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Attendees supported more immediate and far-reaching action on climate change.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Glasgow City Council and most neighbouring councils stated that students would not be punished if parents informed their schools of the absence.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 6 November—the Global Day of Action for Climate Justice—around 100,000 people joined a march in Glasgow, according to BBC News, with coaches and group cycle rides organized for participants to travel from around the United Kingdom.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The protests were the largest in Glasgow since anti-Iraq War marches in 2003.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] A London march drew 10,000 people according to police and 20,000 according to organizers.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] *The Times* anticipated that total participants would number over two million.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] An additional 100 marches took place elsewhere in the country, with a total of 300 protests across 100 countries, according to *The Guardian*.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 8 November, Fridays for Future activists including Dominika Lasota and Nicole Becker held a protest prior to a speech by former US president Barack Obama, arguing that he had failed to fulfill his promise to provide US$100 billion in climate funding to developing countries.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The protestors held banners stating, "Show us the money".
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Vanessa Nakate and indigenous activists gave speeches at Glasgow.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Issues highlighted by protesters included putting corporate interests at the forefront and politicians' failure to address the climate emergency with the required urgency as well as its underlying causes.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Kahnawake Mohawk people, ecology scientists, vegan activists, trade unionists and socialists were present at marches.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] One intended participant, the Israeli energy minister Karine Elharrar, was unable to attend on 1 November due to wheelchair accessibility issues.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The sustainability of the COP26 menu was criticized by the animal and climate justice group Animal Rebellion, with almost 60% of the menu being meat and dairy based, and dishes labelled as high-carbon being served at food stands.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The head of catering at COP26, Lorna Wilson, said that staff had been "working towards" a catering strategy of 95% food from the UK and 5% from abroad.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Wilson said the menu was 40% plant-based and 60% vegetarian overall.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The event eliminated single-use cups and plastics.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] There was concern about the inclusion and influence of large delegations of industries, particularly big polluting companies, and financial organizations involved in the causes of greenhouse gas emissions at the conference.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Further criticisms of the results include that it needs not only commitments but also clear directions for mitigation and adaptation and robust mechanisms put in place for the relevant parties to be held accountable to their commitments.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] According to critics, such issues could turn the conference into a "greenwashing" event of empty promises.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] There is a criticism about the lack of people from most affected people and areas.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Kaossara Sani became one of the persons who came from this place and sent her criticism by sending her manifesto to Forbes about what happened in Sahel and her criticism to COP26.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Academicians and practitioners on the field have floated several missing links of COP26 particularly the approach to climate change, disasters and public health consequences stemming from the meeting and how the neglect of healthcare will impact the Asia Pacific Region as a whole.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] According to the Institute for Strategic Dialogue and a network of journalism organizations, the COP meeting became a target for climate misinformation, prominently "narratives of delay".
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 9 November, Climate Action Tracker reported that the global human civilization is on track for a 2.7 °C temperature increase in the Earth system by the end of the century with current policies.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The temperature will rise by 2.4 °C if the pledges for 2030 will be implemented, by 2.1 °C if the long-term targets will be implemented also and by 1.8 °C if in addition all the targets in discussion will be fully implemented.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Current targets for 2030 remain "totally inadequate".
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Coal and natural gas consumption are the main cause for the gap between pledges and policies.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 10 November, it was reported that the United States and China agreed on a framework to reduce carbon emissions by cooperating on measures to lower the use of methane, phase out the use of coal and increased protection of forests.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The request was criticized as illogical and self-defeating as it would end up harming people in developing countries the most and an article in the *Daily Beast* described the request as an attempt by China to sabotage the draft commitment.
[src:animal-rising/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] China was responsible for around 27% of the world's current GHG emissions in 2019.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] The **2023 Grand National** (officially known as the **Randox 2023 Grand National** for sponsorship reasons) was the 175th annual running of the Grand National horse race.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] It took place on Saturday 15 April 2023, at Aintree Racecourse near Liverpool, England.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] The event was sponsored by Randox Health with Natasha Jonas acting as ambassador.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] The race was won by Corach Rambler who was trained by Lucinda Russell in Scotland and ridden by Irish jockey Derek Fox, who had both previously won the Grand National in 2017 with One For Arthur.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] The race start was delayed by 14 minutes, following protests by campaign group Animal Rising, the first such disruptions since the cancellation of the 1993 Grand National due to a series of false starts and the 1997 Grand National due to the IRA bomb threat.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Merseyside Police made 118 arrests, for both "criminal damage and public nuisance offences".
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] The initial entry of 85 horses was published on 7 February 2023.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Only 31 of the horses entered were trained in Great Britain, compared to 54 in the initial entry for the 2022 race.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Of the Irish-trained runners, 21 were trained by Gordon Elliott, who was seeking a fourth Grand National victory as a trainer.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Bookmakers made 2022 winner Noble Yeats 10-1 favourite at the time of the entries.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Weight for the race were announced on 21 February 2023.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Three horses were given the top weight of 11 stones and 12 pounds; Any Second Now (the 2022 runner-up), Conflated and Hewick.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Galvin and Noble Yeats were just behind on 11 stone 11, and Noble Yeats remained the betting favourite at a best price of 11-1.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Publication of the weights opened up the possibility that the final field would be dominated by Irish-trained runners, with 41 of the top 60 in the weights trained in Ireland.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Nine horses were withdrawn at the acceptance stage on 7 March.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Amongst the withdrawals were the 2021 winner Minella Times, who had been retired, and the fourth-placed horse from 2021 Burrows Saint.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Iwilldoit was withdrawn having failed to meet the requirements of running in six steeplechases before 19 February.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] The withdrawals left 73 possible runners remaining with the next acceptance stage due on 28 March.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] A further sixteen horses were withdrawn at the 28 March acceptance stage to leave 57 possible runners.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] The fifth-placed horse from 2021, Farclas, was amongst the withdrawals and other notable scratchings included Becher Chase winner Ashtown Lad and the 2022 Irish Grand National winner Lord Lariat.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] The betting at this stage was headed by 6-1 chance Corach Rambler, who had won the Ultima Handicap Chase for a second consecutive year, followed by Noble Yeats at 8-1.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Only Any Second Now remained from the three top-weighted horses as Conflated and Hewick were withdrawn.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Final confirmations were made on 10 April and seven more horses were withdrawn, leaving 50 possible runners.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Corach Rambler remained as the general 6-1 betting favourite with Noble Yeats at 8-1 and Delta Work at 10-1.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] The 40 runners were finalised on Thursday 13 April.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] There were no withdrawals at Thursday's declaration stage.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] In a change from previous years, no reserves were declared.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Escaria Ten, who finished ninth in the 2022 race, was declared a non-runner on the day.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] lead commentator Richard Hoiles describes the climax of the race.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] As the Grand National is accorded the status of an event of national interest in the United Kingdom and is listed on the Ofcom Code on Sports and Other Listed and Designated Events, it must be shown on free-to-air terrestrial television in the UK.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] The race was broadcast live on TV by ITV for the sixth time, and the final year in its current three year deal with the British Horseracing Authority.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] The ITV coverage was presented by Ed Chamberlin and Adele Mulrennan.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Analysis was provided by former jockeys Sir Anthony McCoy, Mick Fitzgerald, Tom Scudamore, Harry Cobden and Ruby Walsh.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Reports were provided by Alice Plunkett, Luke Harvey, Rishi Persad and Matt Chapman, and betting updates were provided by Brian Gleeson.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Oli Bell and Chris Hughes covered viewers' comments on social media, while Mark Heyes and Charlotte Hawkins were chatting to the crowd on Ladies Day.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] The commentary team was Mark Johnson, Stewart Machin and Richard Hoiles, who called the finish for the sixth time.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Following the race, Bell and Walsh guided viewers on a fence-by-fence re-run of the race.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Hill Sixteen fell and was mortally injured at the first fence, killing him almost instantly.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] The trainer of Hill Sixteen, Sandy Thomson, claimed that the horse became "hyper" because of the protests, which led to him not taking off at the first fence.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Thomson was adamant that the actions of the protesters were behind his horse falling for the first time in his career.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Hill Sixteen had previously ridden 27 races on 15 different tracks, and had previously jumped the Grand National fences at Aintree while competing twice in the Becher Chase .
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Earlier at the Aintree meeting Envoye Special had been euthanised, following an injury after a fall in the Foxhunters' Open Hunters' Chase and Dark Raven had been euthanised after a fall at the Turners Mersey Novice Hurdle.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Animal rights campaign group Animal Rising had threatened to disrupt the race and were protesting from early on the day of the race.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] 118 people were arrested over protests that delayed the start of race by 14 minutes.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] Merseyside Police held nine people who had been able to enter the track and later said arrests had been made for both "criminal damage and public nuisance offences", including arrests made before the race and connected to a protest that had blocked the M57.
[src:animal-rising/2023-grand-national] This was the third Grand National to be disrupted in post-war history since the 1993 Grand National which led to a series of false starts and the 1997 Grand National was postponed to Monday because of an IRA bomb threat.
[src:animal-rising/2024-grand-national] The **2024 Grand National** (officially known as the **Randox 2024 Grand National** for sponsorship reasons) was the 176th annual running of the Grand National horse race.
[src:animal-rising/2024-grand-national] It took place on Saturday 13 April 2024, at Aintree Racecourse near Liverpool, England.
[src:animal-rising/2024-grand-national] The event was sponsored by Randox Health.
[src:animal-rising/2024-grand-national] Changes from previous races were the reduction of horses from 40 to 34 and an earlier start time of 4pm, compared to 5.15pm in 2023.
[src:animal-rising/2024-grand-national] It was won by bookies' favourite I Am Maximus, who was trained by Willie Mullins and ridden by Paul Townend.
[src:animal-rising/2024-grand-national] Two horses, Run Wild Fred and Chambard, were withdrawn on the morning of the race after being found lame, reducing the field to 32 runners, the smallest field since the 1999 Grand National which also had 32 runners.
[src:animal-rising/2024-grand-national] A total of 21 out of 32 horses finished the race, leaving 11 non-finishers.
[src:animal-rising/2024-grand-national] Seven horses were pulled up, and four were due to unseated riders.
[src:animal-rising/2024-grand-national] While concerns were expressed for Mac Tottie, who was treated by veterinarians at the scene, all the horses returned safely.
[src:animal-rising/2024-grand-national] However, over the course of the 3 day meeting, if not over the Grand National fences, there were two equine fatalities.
[src:animal-rising/2024-grand-national] The race was broadcast live on TV by ITV for the seventh time, and the first year in its new three year deal with the British Horseracing Authority.
[src:animal-rising/2024-grand-national] The ITV coverage was presented by Ed Chamberlin.
[src:animal-rising/2024-grand-national] Analysis was provided by former jockeys Sir Anthony McCoy, Mick Fitzgerald, and Ruby Walsh.
[src:animal-rising/2024-grand-national] Reports were provided by Alice Plunkett, Adele Mulrennan, Luke Harvey, Rishi Persad and Matt Chapman, and betting updates were provided by Brian Gleeson.
[src:animal-rising/2024-grand-national] Oli Bell covered viewers' comments on social media, and the commentary team was Mark Johnson, Stewart Machin and Richard Hoiles, who called the finish for the seventh time.
[src:animal-rising/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:animal-rising/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:animal-rising/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:animal-rising/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:animal-rising/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:animal-rising/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:animal-rising/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:animal-rising/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:animal-rising/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:animal-rising/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:animal-rising/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:animal-rising/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:animal-rising/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:animal-rising/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:animal-rising/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:animal-rising/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] Animal Rising use civil disobedience methods that have frequently resulted in its members being arrested.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] Their methods include graffiti, destruction of property, blockading and preventing food distribution, trespassing onto livestock industry premises, and blockading streets.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] The movement states on its website that it is nonviolent and focuses its actions on systems, not individuals.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] The targets of their actions have included dairy and other livestock companies, horse racing courses, the British royal family, government offices, supermarkets, and restaurants.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] The organisation was founded in June 2019 as Animal Rebellion, as a sister organisation to Extinction Rebellion, an emerging and headline-making movement at the time.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] It had 12 founding members, including Daniel Kidby and Alex Lockwood, and by autumn 2019 grew to a size of 100 organisers.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] In April 2023, Animal Rebellion changed its name to Animal Rising to take a "firm" step away from the Extinction Rebellion movement and prioritize animal rights issues.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] Animal Rising pledged to "take direct action to see an end to animal suffering in all its forms".
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] From 7 October to 19 October 2019, Animal Rebellion organised a wave of civil disobedience in London and Berlin, in parallel to Extinction Rebellion protests.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] They reported that the abattoir protest was to highlight the role the farming industry plays in the climate crisis, as well as animal welfare issues and the conditions for abattoir workers.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] In 2020, Animal Rebellion staged protests in the UK, Ireland and the Czech Republic in September.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] This included the blockade of a pig slaughterhouse near Manchester, England.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] In London, they vandalised the Trafalgar Square fountain by dying the water red, resulting in two arrests and a bill for the council to clean the water.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] This was to protest the use of crown lands for hunting and animal agriculture, as well as the Queen's attempts to have her land exempted from an initiative to cut carbon emissions.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] In October, Animal Rebellion protested in Berlin (Germany) and Auckland (New Zealand).
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] Animal Rebellion protesters blocked the entrance of a Tnuva dairy logistics centre in Petah Tikva, Israel, in February 2021.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] Similarly, Animal Rebellion blocked the entrances of four McDonald's UK distribution centres in May 2021, demanding the fast-food chain go entirely plant-based by 2025.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] An Animal Rebellion spokesperson said that what others call sustainable meat is insufficient to mitigate the climate crisis.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] Continuing their attack on McDonald's, the group blocked the entrance to the OSI Food Solutions factory in Scunthorpe, England in July 2021.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] The factory is the "only UK factory that makes McDonald's burgers", Animal Rebellion stated.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] Like the protest in May, they demanded the chain change their menu to entirely plant-based food by 2025.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] On 28 August 2021, they coordinated a protest with Camp Beagle at Smithfield Market in London.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] During that month, they also held a "McSitin" at Leicester Square, dyed the fountain in front of Buckingham Palace red and blocked the trucks of Arla's biggest UK dairy processing plant which is in Aylesbury.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] During the annual UN Climate Change conference COP26 in October 2021, Animal Rebellion protesters climbed the Home Office building.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] On 2 June 2022, Animal Rebellion in London disrupted the trooping the colour parade, running into the Mall and throwing themselves in front of the procession, in a renewed protest against the royal family's support of animal agriculture.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] Two days later, six female protesters ran onto the course of the Epsom Derby horse race before its start.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] The action was on the anniversary of Emily Davison's famous suffragette protest at the same derby 109 years earlier.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] In both cases, the activists were removed by police officers and were arrested.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] On 8 August 2022, the protesters stormed the Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals (RSPCA), and occupied the national headquarters.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] They refused to leave the building, blocking the front doors and hosting impromptu workshops until the RSPCA agreed to declare its support for transitioning to a fully plant-based food system.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] In June 2022, a group of protesters stormed Harrods and another store in London.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] They took cartons of milk and emptied them in the stores.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] In early September 2022, Animal Rebellion declared it would disrupt dairy supplies during September.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] On 3 September, activists blocked access to milk at supermarkets in four cities.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] On 4 September, activists disrupted fresh milk supplies at four Müller and Arla distribution centres.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] In mid-October 2022, activists from Animal Rebellion held protests by pouring milk on the floor in various stores and supermarkets across Britain, including Harrods, Marks & Spencer, Waitrose and Fortnum & Mason.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] In November 2022, Animal Rebellion members joined Just Stop Oil in a protest on the M25 motorway in the UK.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] Also in November 2022, they occupied Gordon Ramsay's three-star Michelin restaurant in Chelsea, London.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] On 14 February 2023, Animal Rebellion blocked London's Westminster Bridge in a Valentine's Day protest.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] This led to the arrest of five Animal Rebellion protesters.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] One additional person was arrested for bodily assaulting the protesters.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] In early April 2023, it was revealed that Animal Rebellion planned to disrupt the 2023 Grand National horse race at Aintree Racecourse.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] Animal Rebellion then renamed itself Animal Rising.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] On April 15, Animal Rising blocked the Grand National at Aintree.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] They delayed the race by 15 minutes, leading to the arrest of 118 activists for delaying the race and for public order offences.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] A spokesman for Aintree Racecourse stated that "their actions could endanger the horses they purport to protect, as well as jockeys, officials and themselves".
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] The next day, trainer Sandy Thomson told the BBC that the 14-minute delay caused by protesters was to blame for the death of racehorse Hill Sixteen.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] However, the British Horseracing Authority, which condemned the protests, could not find a "direct parallel" between the delay caused by the protests and Hill Sixteen's death.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] Animal Rising spokesman Ben Newman argued that the protests were meant to stop the race to prevent the deaths of horses, and to start a dialogue about our broken relationship with animals.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] He also stated that the public does not blame the group for the horse's death.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] Following Hill Sixteen's death, the RSPCA called for reforming the size of the field, noting that only 17 of the 39 horses completed the race that day.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] Animal Rising stated they planned to target other major horse racing events.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] The group attempted to disrupt that year's Epsom Derby but failed, with only a single individual making it onto the track before being removed without impacting the races.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] Plans to disrupt the Royal Ascot were abandoned by the group.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] In April 2024, the group stated it wouldn't attempt to disrupt the 2024 Grand National, and that it would be indefinitely suspending similar actions.
[src:animal-rising/animal-rising] In June 2024, protestors attached posters depicting Wallace, of *Wallace and Gromit*, with a caption, to the glass case of a recently unveiled portrait of King Charles III in protest against the conditions in "assured farms" accredited by the RSPCA, of which the King is a patron.
